3. Repository Structure
tanzania_corridor_propagation_architecture/

├── data_raw/              # Original EO and socioeconomic datasets
├── data_processed/        # Cleaned and harmonized datasets
├── weights_matrices/      # Corridor-based spatial weights matrices
├── scripts/               # Modeling and processing scripts
├── figures/               # Publication-ready figures
├── results/               # Model outputs
├── replication/           # Reproducibility instructions
└── docs/                  # Supplementary documentation

This structure follows best practices for computational reproducibility in spatial modeling.

4. Data Sources

Data include:

Sentinel-2 derived EO indicators

Regional socioeconomic statistics

Corridor definitions (infrastructure-based)

Spatial boundary data (Tanzania administrative regions)

EO preprocessing and feature extraction follow standardized geospatial workflows.

Restricted or licensed data are not redistributed but are described in the manuscript.

5. Computational Environment

Recommended environment:

R (≥ 4.2) or Python (≥ 3.10)

Required spatial packages:

spdep

sf

spatialreg

raster

terra

rgdal

tidyverse

All required packages are listed within the /replication/ folder.

6. Reproducibility Workflow

Execution order:

01_data_preparation

02_corridor_matrix_construction

03_model_estimation

04_spillover_analysis

05_figure_generation

All intermediate outputs are stored in /data_processed/ and /results/.

The pipeline is fully modular to allow extension or adaptation to other geographic contexts.

7. Methodological Innovation

This repository introduces:

Corridor-constrained spatial weights construction

Infrastructure-based spillover modeling

EO-integrated SDM architecture

Directionally restricted spatial propagation framework

The approach extends traditional spatial econometric models by embedding physical development corridors directly into the spatial interaction matrix.

8. Intended Use

This repository supports:

Replication of published results

Extension of corridor-based modeling to other regions

Testing alternative corridor definitions

Comparative analysis with classical spatial weights

It is not intended for direct policy decision-making without contextual validation.

9. Citation

If using this framework, please cite:

Sitenda, A. (2026). Corridor-Based Spatial Propagation Modeling Using EO Data and Spatial Durbin Framework: Evidence from Tanzania. Submitted to International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation.

